The uprising had other consequences.

The traitor Lucas Sazon was executed, and his pregnant wife sent into exile. As further punishment, Iza -- the capital city of Brenas, and the Sazons' ancestral home -- was handed over to your family.

Your uncle Hugo was sent to serve as its steward. In turn, you were to take his place as reigning Duke of Valenqiris.

After the funeral, your mother Estela came to visit and found you hardly able to function. She promptly moved in to help out with Vina. 

Hugo suggested you turn to Wruhecism, Rizia's official religion, to cope with your loss.

Hugo suggested you turn to Wruhecism, Rizia's official religion, to cope with your loss.

Narrator

Meanwhile, the situation in the capital worsened.\n\nRizian nationalists continued to protest the loss of Zille and the country's increasing diversity. Rumors spread that an anti-monarchist movement was beginning to grow once more.\n\nYour father called Hugo back from Iza to keep an eye on his council.

Narrator

The king insisted you be driven back to the capital immediately.

As you left Montaklar, though, an unmarked car swerved in front of you, blocking the road.

A trio of masked men with guns jumped out, quickly overpowered your guards and forced you out of the vehicle.

Player_Romus

You tried to fight them.

Narrator

Your captors subdued you after only the slightest struggle. 

You recognized one of their voices: Lucas Sazon, Duke of Brenas and the head of Rizia's third royal house.

A hood went over your head.

Narrator

At the palace, you pieced together what had happened.

In desperation, your father had pleaded for the aid of a neighboring country, Wehlen, to neutralize the uprising.

But their help came at a price. Over the next year, the two countries worked out an agreement for the temporary transfer of the port of Zille and its surrounding region -- home to gold, oil and millions of people.

For the next 25 years, Zille would belong to Wehlen.

Valenqiris came to see you as a generous, capable leader.\n\nOne day, the king came for an unannounced visit. He brought with him a pale-skinned young woman with striking blue eyes.\n\nHesitantly, she introduced herself as Lena Livingston -- the sister of Queen Beatrice of Rumburg, and your wife-to-be.

You were in your office when you got the call.

The weather had turned stormy in the middle of the Gulf of Valenqiris. When the captain tried to turn the boat around, it was hit by a breaking wave and cracked in half.

The coast guard managed to save Vina on time. But by the time they pulled your wife out, she was barely breathing.

You rushed to the hospital.

You slowly realized that the uprising had broken something in your father.\n\nHe began neglecting his duties as he became increasingly preoccupied with threats, both real and imaginary. \n\nOutside of the country, he gained a new nickname.

Narrator

You stayed close with your father in the months that followed, though you were both too busy to see each other as often as you would have liked. \n\nAs Vina grew into an intelligent, self-reliant young woman, your mother moved from Monqiz back to the capital.\n\nShe called you one night, her voice shaking.
